sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: ADS Zone.Identifier Deleted By Uncommon Application
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the deletion of the "Zone.Identifier" ADS by an uncommon process. Attackers can leverage this in order to bypass security restrictions that make use of the ADS such as Microsoft Office apps.
Detects the creation of screensaver files (.scr) outside of system folders. Attackers may execute an application as an ".SCR" file using "rundll32.exe desk.cpl,InstallScreenSaver" for example.

Adversaries may establish persistence by executing malicious content triggered by user inactivity.
Screensavers are programs that execute after a configurable time of user inactivity and consist of Portable Executable (PE) files with a .scr file extension

Detects modification of the registry settings used for Internet Explorer and other Windows components that use these settings. An attacker can abuse this registry key to add a domain to the trusted sites Zone or insert javascript for persistence

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a malicious dropper/downloader that employs several evasion and social engineering techniques. Key behaviors include: 1) Extensive string obfuscation using a custom XOR/NOT decryption routine (sub_401000) to hide API names and library strings. 2) Dynamic API resolution via LoadLibraryA and GetProcAddress to bypass static IAT analysis. 3) Network/File activity evidenced by the hardcoded User-Agent (Chrome 109) and calls to DeleteUrlCacheEntryW. 4) Payload execution logic in sub_401060 which constructs a random filename with a '.scr' extension in the %TEMP% directory, writes data to it, and executes it. 5) Use of a decoy 'MessageBoxA' error ('mwpnt32q.dll could not be found') to deceive the user while the malicious payload runs in the background. Relevant IOCs include the %TEMP%\.scr file pattern and the specific decoy DLL name.
